SIMPLE: cognation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cognation
<hw>Cog*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>cognatio</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Relationship by blood;
descent from the same original; kindred.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As by our <qex>cognation</qex> to the body of the first Adam.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Participation of the same nature.</def> <rj><au>Sir
T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A like temper and <qex>cognation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir K.
Digby.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>That tie of consanguinity which
exists between persons descended from the same mother; -- used in
distinction from <contr>agnation</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cognatus</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
